metadata.name: Willie's Nightmare Cash Grab #160
metadata.description:
Through extensive lobbying, Disney helped change copyright law through the Copyright Term Extension Act to keep Mickey's earliest incarnation, Steamboat Willie, out of the public domain for an extra 20 years. While copyright law often protects artists, it shouldn't last forever. Thankfully, more hybridized forms of protection such as Creative Commons licenses have emerged allowing for protection as well as remixes and reimaginations. 

With Steamboat Willie now in the public domain, this collection builds upon Willie (and Disney's) nightmare of all sorts of off-brand chaos inflicted upon his form, transforming Mickey from an icon of family-friendly magic to one of nightmarish capitalism, sexual freedom, and murder run rampant. 

No commentary on the clash of capitalism and art would be complete without making this an open edition with a treasure hunt of trait pairings. The hunt will last as long as the open edition (two weeks), and after that, prizes shall be airdropped. 

For more information and to claim prizes, please join the House of Mors Discord: https://discord.gg/3N2KBfUuAN

Thanks to PureSpider for the image composition tool.

metadata.name: Neural Tapestry #14
metadata.description:
Tapestry knitting machine is considered to be a prototype of the computer. Over time, computers began to weave again, composing ornaments and plots. A long time has passed since then, and computer carpets are stored in digital museums, forcing the viewer to view their illegible panoramic images. They are like words that were spoken long time ago, like legends about the wars of robots and octopuses that smart vacuum cleaners tell each other.

Ornaments are best viewed in live mode.

Images are generated with customised VQGAN+CLIP Python code.

metadata.name: Terra #88
metadata.description:
The year is 2242. Humanity is desperate to find new habitable planets to escape a dying earth. To aid this process of space colonization, multiple drones have been released across galactic sectors on this large scale reconnaissance mission. This is a fragment of a larger speculative series investigating the concepts of space and time in the era of post-human condition.

This piece consists of five landscape types and six drone classes generated procedurally using noise and basic geometric shapes, driven by the seed to generate unique iterations.

Hit 's' to take a high-resolution(4096x4096) screenshot.

metadata.name: Offset Disorder #69
metadata.description:
This work is an experiment using generated risograph halftones and hand-drawn elements to create a highly textured pattern. 

- Viewing in Chrome is recommended.
- Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. 
- Image size is 1200x1200px.

Common Features:
- Random 3 to 10 color palette using colors from p5riso
- Individual color layer shifts from 2 to 20px
- Simplex or square color noise patters
- Glitches resulting in hand-drawn shapes
- Glitch rate of 10-50% of shapes

Less Common
- Linear color distribution (top -> bottom)
- Up to 5 large hand-drawn circles
- Very high glitch rate of 50%

Rare
- Perfect color alignment with no errors

metadata.name: Silver Rectangles #7
metadata.description:
Silver Ratio = 0.618... is the inverse of the famous Golden Ratio (1.618...)

In this piece, I used the silver ratio to divide the rectangles into more rectangles.
I started with one rectangle, whose height/width ratio is Silver Ratio, then divided the longer side in two, according to the Silver Ratio. Newly formed two rectangles undergo the same algorithm and so it goes on.

There are three different textures for rectangles, with equal probability.
Colors are used in a way that makes it easier to follow the flow of division that took place.

If you look closely, you can identify the 'companion' rectangle to any rectangle, which means they were one rectangle before the last division.

Best viewed in full screen view.

In the end, I want to thank Tyler Hobbs for his essays on generative art. His writings taught me a lot about colors and shapes and balance in generative art.

(Remaining tokens will be burned after a week)

metadata.name: fxFrog #97
metadata.description:
The wood frog of North America actually freezes in the winter and is reanimated in the spring. When temperatures fall, the wood frog’s body begins to shut down, and its breathing, heartbeat and muscle movements stop. The water in the frog’s cells freezes and is replaced with glucose and urea to keep cells from collapsing. When there’s a thaw, the frog’s warms up, its body functions resume and it hops off like nothing ever happened.

by krchr 2022

metadata.name: Cellular Skyscrapers #185
metadata.description:
A "Cellular Skyscraper" originates from a 15x15 grid with 15x3 cells randomly assigned the 'alive' state. According to the cellular automaton rule chosen from the transaction hash 24 new generations are calculated and placed on top of each other.

There are four different rules available (listed in Golly notation) all based on the Moore neighbourhood: 

B3/S23 (Game of Life)
B36/S125 (2x2)
B368/S245 (Morley)
B3/S234 (didn't find a name for it but produces interesting large structures)

After all generations have been calculated the algorithm searches through the complete 3D grid to find the one structure consisting of the most connected alive cells - cells are connected when they have at least one alive neighbour in any of the three axis.

Features are cell count, height, highlight color, ca rule and antenna count.

Extra: press 'd' to download the structure as a .gltf file to import into Blender or other software.
 
Enjoy!

metadata.name: Countdown #34
metadata.description:
80% of the benefits from primary sales will go to the nonprofit "One Earth", check out their mission and their projects in www.oneearth.org

---------------

We need your help! The Earth is melting!

"Countdown" is a project that tries to show some consequences of global warming and pollution. It does so by representing a glacier that will melt over time, acting as a Countdown for our time left to react to the Climate Crisis.

If you visit this token every other day, the melting will start to be noticeable, and around one year, most of the ice will be gone. The token will also show signs of pollution: the sky colors will desaturate, stars will be less visible on night palettes, and the ice and water will get dirtier. Lastly, the penguin families will start disappearing, as the ice melts and they lose their home.

All the information of the token is available on the browser's console (Features + Token evolution).

---------------
- 365 editions, as the ice will melt almost completely in one year
- 13 color palettes, with different rarities
- 3 ice shades
- Different number of penguin families
---------------

Press "s" to save a 2000x2000px png with the current state of the token

metadata.name: Tessellatum #12
metadata.description:
Tessellatum – a collection inspired by mosaic and weaving craftworks.

The artworks were created by applying a p5.js generative algorithm simulating mosaic, pointillism and weaving-like textures on a library of images issued/exported from a generative flowfield algorithm in R (The R Project for Statistical Computing). In other words, to avoid any ambiguity, the R issued images on which the mosaics effects are applied are not generated on the fxhash platform, but the mosaic effects (noise, size and shape of the tiles), the backgrounds and various other generative elements are via a p5.js implementation.
